            "title": "Understanding formulaic language : a second language acquisition perspective",
            "abstract": [
                "Formulaic language: setting the scene / Anna Siyanova-Chanturia and Ana Pellicer-S\u00e1nchez -- Acquisition of formulaic language from a usage-based perspective / Stefanie Wulff -- What on-line processing tells us about formulaic language / Anna Siyanova-Chanturia and Diana Van Lancker Sidtis -- First language influence on the processing of formulaic language in a second language / Kathy Conklin and Gareth Carrol -- Formulaic language and speech prosody / Phoebe Lin -- Formulaic language in second language pragmatics research / Kathleen Bardovi-Harlig -- Humour and formulaic language in second language learning / Nancy Bell and Stephen Skalicky -- Formulaic language and its place in intercultural pragmatics / Istvan Kecskes -- Pedagogical approaches to the teaching and learning of formulaic language / Ana Pellicer-S\u00e1nchez and Frank Boers -- Testing of formulaic language / Henrik Gyllstad and Norbert Schmitt -- From corpus to CALL: The use of technology in teaching and learning of formulaic language / Tom Cobb -- Formulaic language in English for academic purposes / Phil Durrant -- Formulaic language in learner corpora / Sylviane Granger -- Why don't second language learners more proactively target formulaic sequences? / Alison Wray",
                "\"Multi- and interdisciplinary in nature, Understanding Formulaic Language brings together leading researchers in the field to provide a state-of-the-art account of what is known about the acquisition, processing, and use of formulaic language, focusing, in particular, on the recent developments and directions for future research. Three distinct but complementary perspectives on the study of formulaic language are presented - the cognitive and psycholinguistic, socio-cultural and pragmatic, and pedagogical - attesting to a rich research base. Understanding Formulaic Language: A Second Language Acquisition Perspective is an essential resource for established researchers and graduate students in second language acquisition and pedagogy, corpus and cognitive linguistics, psycholinguistics, sociolinguistics, and pragmatics\"--"
